reau who experimented with regimens of simplified living and transcendental mysticism, Smith shows how disciplines of attention became the spiritual exercises of a distracted age.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 0aAmerican literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aDiscipline in literature. 0aDisciplinexIn literature. 0aDistraction (Psychology) in literature. 0aDistraction (Psychology)xIn literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh  aAchievement (heraldry).  aAcquiescence.  aActivism.  aAesthetics.  aAnimal magnetism.  aAsceticism.  aAttention economy.  aAuthor.  aBacksliding.  aBernard Bailyn.  aBernard Stiegler.  aBig business.  aBiography.  aByzantine Empire.  aCamp meeting.  aCapital punishment.  aCapitalism.  aCareer.  aCatechism.  aChristian revival.  aChristianity.  aChurch architecture.  aClassroom.  aColored.  aConversion narrative.  aCounterculture.  aCriticism.  aDefinition of religion.  aDissociation (psychology).  aDistraction.  aDivine judgment.  aEthics.  aEvangelicalism.  aHannah Arendt.  aHannah More.  aHarvard University Press.  aHenry David Thoreau.  aHypocrisy.  aIdentity politics.  aImperialism.  aIndulgence.  aIrritability.  aLaborer.  aLearning.  aLeaves of Grass.  aLegal fiction.  aLethargy.  aLife Without Principle.  aListening.  aLiterary genre.  aLiterature.  aLydia Maria Child.  aMarket Revolution.  aMeditations.  aMethodism.  aModernity.  aNat Turner.  aNonconformist.  aObedience (human behavior).  aOf Education.  aOppression.  aOxford University Press.  aPamphlet.  aPhilosopher.  aPiety.  aPoetry.  aPolitical culture.  aPrejudice.  aPrinceton University Press.  aProse.  aProtestantism.  aRacialism.  aReformato